INSERT [dbo].[ProjectPool] ([ID], [Title], [Description], [DocumentURL], [GroupSize], [CreatedAt], [UpdatedAt], [SupervisorID], [SkillsRequest]) VALUES (15, N'Mining students solutions to the programming exercises for knowledge discovery', N'Success and failure in introductory programming courses has intrigued researchers and educators for decades. Studies on retention posit that, on average, one third of students in an introductory programming course either withdraw or fail. In this project, a collection of students solution to the assignments of an introductory programming module will be analyzed. The project includes three main phases including a) Data extraction and transformation, b) Data analysis in a text mining framework, and c) mining the data in order to identify common response patterns in their answers.', NULL, 2, CAST(N'2017-08-24T11:53:23.707' AS DateTime), CAST(N'2017-08-24T11:53:23.707' AS DateTime), 18, NULL)
INSERT [dbo].[ProjectPool] ([ID], [Title], [Description], [DocumentURL], [GroupSize], [CreatedAt], [UpdatedAt], [SupervisorID], [SkillsRequest]) VALUES (16, N'Prediction of students course outcome using machine learning', N'It has always been the computer science researcher''s interest to determine poor performing students at the early stages of the semester. Identification of these students helps the instructors and the lectures of the programming course to consider specific plans for the students who might be in need of assistance. In this project, students attempts in completing a set of programming exercises will be analyzed to identify present patterns which explain students engagement with the course and its relationship with the course outcome in an introductory programming module. This project will be carried in two main phases including a) collecting, transforming, and storing students attempts into a relational database, and b) performing machine learning tasks for pattern recognition purposes.', NULL, 3, CAST(N'2017-08-24T12:02:16.973' AS DateTime), CAST(N'2017-08-24T12:02:16.973' AS DateTime), 18, NULL)
INSERT [dbo].[ProjectPool] ([ID], [Title], [Description], [DocumentURL], [GroupSize], [CreatedAt], [UpdatedAt], [SupervisorID], [SkillsRequest]) VALUES (17, N'visualising patient journeys though the health system', N'Epidemiologist are skilled at producing descriptive statistics that aid understanding the prevalence and incidence of disease ad a function of many important factors. In the same way, health systems analysts use descriptive statistics that aid understanding for how health services and resources are used. This can be used to inform policy and programs for running a state’s health system.

This approach is fine when the events of interest are taken to be independent. It is harder to gain insight for more complicated scenarios. For example patients with chronic conditions access multiple health services in complex ways. This realisation is driving initiatives such as “Health Care Homes” and “Integrated Care.” The challenge is how to use and present health system data in ways that gives statistical insight not into individual service events, but into patient’s journeys.

NSW Ministry of Health has access to data from hospital admissions, emergency department presentations, and general practice visits. These datasets are linked such that the events for individuals are grouped.

The aim of the project is to explore ways to use and present data available to NSW Ministry of Health to gain statistical insight into the journeys of patients with chronic conditions.
', N'~/Resources/projectpool/b76168c4-7fdf-4159-8645-11e917b907af-researchprojectdes.docx', 2, CAST(N'2018-03-11T23:57:58.000' AS DateTime), CAST(N'2018-03-22T05:19:28.113' AS DateTime), 3, N'Be familiar with a data visualisation software framework.
Be familiar with common data visualisation techniques.
Good English speaking and writing skills.')
INSERT [dbo].[ProjectPool] ([ID], [Title], [Description], [DocumentURL], [GroupSize], [CreatedAt], [UpdatedAt], [SupervisorID], [SkillsRequest]) VALUES (18, N'Real-time marine animal surveillance and population estimation from aerial imagery- phase 2 ', N'A real-time marine animal detection and surveying system has to be developed using the latest advances in Deep Learning. The system will detect different marine animals from image/videos captured using Unmanned Aerial Vehicles near beaches and other areas of interest. The system will be also used for aerial surveillance and estimating population of various marine animals, particularly endangered species, to facilitate the development of appropriate conservation strategies. Government agencies and other organizations responsible for aerial surveillance and saving lives on our beaches are the potential users of the project outcomes.
